1
00:00:00,400 --> 00:00:02,160
Hello and welcome.

2
00:00:03,226 --> 00:00:07,756
AI DevKit is an operating model for AI-centric software engineering.

3
00:00:09,381 --> 00:00:13,282
AI writes specs, tests, code, and docs.

4
00:00:14,689 --> 00:00:17,603
Humans approve the spec and approve the release.

5
00:00:19,028 --> 00:00:22,164
It works with your existing stack — git,

6
00:00:22,271 --> 00:00:27,521
repos, pull requests, continuous integration — and reshapes it around

7
00:00:27,681 --> 00:00:32,329
AI execution, while keeping the human checkpoints that matter.

8
00:00:33,917 --> 00:00:36,484
There are four pillars: spec planning,

9
00:00:36,692 --> 00:00:42,167
test-driven implementation, progressive disclosure docs, and

10
00:00:42,207 --> 00:00:44,008
the AI dev environment.

11
00:00:44,276 --> 00:00:45,923
Work comes in as a story,

12
00:00:46,004 --> 00:00:47,685
epic, bug, or feature.

13
00:00:48,950 --> 00:00:52,242
It flows through three phases: Plan,

14
00:00:52,285 --> 00:00:54,087
Implementation, and Release.

15
00:00:55,826 --> 00:00:58,327
The Lead AI executes the workflow.

16
00:01:00,210 --> 00:01:05,131
The Verify AI independently reviews all Lead AI work — it's a

17
00:01:05,188 --> 00:01:07,926
second AI from a different training lineage.

18
00:01:09,420 --> 00:01:10,407
Why two AIs?

19
00:01:11,782 --> 00:01:16,449
A single AI is confidently wrong in ways invisible to itself.

20
00:01:17,378 --> 00:01:21,051
Asking the same model to review its own output rarely catches the

21
00:01:21,103 --> 00:01:21,449
error.

22
00:01:22,949 --> 00:01:26,179
Two independent lineages catch different mistakes.

23
00:01:27,518 --> 00:01:29,617
The Plan phase produces a spec.

24
00:01:31,338 --> 00:01:33,943
The Implementation phase produces working code,

25
00:01:34,022 --> 00:01:35,862
tests, and updated docs.

26
00:01:37,112 --> 00:01:42,656
That deliverable passes through Release — continuous integration and delivery pipelines

27
00:01:42,768 --> 00:01:44,171
plus human approval.

28
00:01:44,570 --> 00:01:47,694
Plan turns a work item into an approved spec.

29
00:01:49,593 --> 00:01:51,852
The Lead AI reads the requirement,

30
00:01:51,871 --> 00:01:57,616
the docs, and the code, then drafts a spec with acceptance criteria,

31
00:01:57,649 --> 00:01:59,777
edge cases, and design decisions.

32
00:02:01,596 --> 00:02:05,340
The Verify AI reviews the spec independently.

33
00:02:06,165 --> 00:02:09,937
If the two AIs disagree on what a criterion means,

34
00:02:10,079 --> 00:02:13,932
that's ambiguity — and it gets surfaced to the human before any

35
00:02:13,996 --> 00:02:15,731
code is written.

36
00:02:16,912 --> 00:02:19,459
The key discipline here: decide in the spec,

37
00:02:19,599 --> 00:02:20,819
not in the code.

38
00:02:22,080 --> 00:02:25,620
If you let the AI defer decisions to implementation,

39
00:02:25,915 --> 00:02:29,308
it makes them implicitly, often inconsistently,

40
00:02:29,451 --> 00:02:31,788
and you only find out when you're reading the code.

41
00:02:33,287 --> 00:02:35,870
The phase ends when the human signs off.

42
00:02:36,651 --> 00:02:41,188
Implementation turns the approved spec into working code.

43
00:02:42,087 --> 00:02:47,348
The Verify AI authors the failing tests directly from the spec.

44
00:02:48,171 --> 00:02:51,794
The Lead AI writes the implementation to make them pass.

45
00:02:52,972 --> 00:02:58,042
This is independent test authorship — the AI that writes the tests

46
00:02:58,175 --> 00:03:01,400
is not the AI that writes the code.

47
00:03:02,324 --> 00:03:07,331
Without that separation, implementation assumptions get silently baked into the

48
00:03:07,451 --> 00:03:08,771
tests.

49
00:03:09,782 --> 00:03:15,254
After test-driven development completes, the Lead AI updates the progressive disclosure docs,

50
00:03:15,638 --> 00:03:20,134
and the Verify AI checks the updates against the actual code.

51
00:03:20,790 --> 00:03:22,776
Then the spec is archived.

52
00:03:23,718 --> 00:03:26,209
The docs carry everything forward.

53
00:03:26,658 --> 00:03:32,045
Progressive Disclosure docs give every repo the same structure.

54
00:03:33,393 --> 00:03:36,036
The same eight files, in every repo,

55
00:03:36,081 --> 00:03:38,042
across the whole organisation.

56
00:03:40,055 --> 00:03:43,881
Level zero is an identity card — what is this repo?

57
00:03:45,510 --> 00:03:48,126
Level one is eight fixed files:

58
00:03:49,324 --> 00:03:54,212
setup, architecture, code map, conventions, workflows,

59
00:03:54,286 --> 00:03:57,496
interfaces, gotchas, and security.

60
00:03:59,509 --> 00:04:04,694
Level two is deep dives, loaded only when Level one isn't enough.

61
00:04:06,740 --> 00:04:10,218
Levels zero and one load upfront — they're small.

62
00:04:11,307 --> 00:04:13,984
Level two is pulled in only when needed.

63
00:04:15,486 --> 00:04:19,826
The agent gets full context without filling the context window.

64
00:04:21,572 --> 00:04:26,154
That consistency is what lets any agent pick up any repo and

65
00:04:26,235 --> 00:04:27,355
work safely.

66
00:04:27,484 --> 00:04:31,275
Real systems span multiple repos — an API,

67
00:04:31,302 --> 00:04:35,193
an SDK, a frontend, shared infrastructure.

68
00:04:35,954 --> 00:04:40,387
The AI dev environment gives you one workspace where the AI can

69
00:04:40,447 --> 00:04:43,105
run the whole system end to end.

70
00:04:44,192 --> 00:04:46,390
It's a container of containers.

71
00:04:47,382 --> 00:04:50,551
Each component runs in its own container,

72
00:04:50,826 --> 00:04:53,429
all inside one outer workspace.

73
00:04:54,448 --> 00:04:57,186
The Lead AI can start, stop,

74
00:04:57,276 --> 00:05:00,468
restart, and test any component from there.

75
00:05:01,489 --> 00:05:03,507
It runs locally or in the cloud.

76
00:05:04,817 --> 00:05:09,511
Cloud workspaces are useful for team handoff — another engineer picks up

77
00:05:09,551 --> 00:05:13,151
the same workspace and the same context.

78
00:05:14,191 --> 00:05:20,471
The environment includes Playwright for browser testing and Terraform for infrastructure.

79
00:05:20,730 --> 00:05:26,468
And there's an audit trail across all agent sessions — reproducibility,

80
00:05:26,536 --> 00:05:31,189
traceability, and evals for debugging agent behaviour.

81
00:05:31,516 --> 00:05:35,427
Everything in AI DevKit runs through six markdown files in a prompts

82
00:05:35,497 --> 00:05:36,551
folder.

83
00:05:37,445 --> 00:05:41,591
spec, implement, create docs, update docs,

84
00:05:41,660 --> 00:05:44,394
verify with Codex, verify with Claude.

85
00:05:45,891 --> 00:05:48,152
They're plain text — you can read them,

86
00:05:48,203 --> 00:05:51,432
understand exactly what the AI is being told to do,

87
00:05:51,492 --> 00:05:53,075
and modify them.

88
00:05:53,985 --> 00:05:58,076
Chain any work prompt with a verify prompt in either direction,

89
00:05:58,120 --> 00:06:00,435
straight from the master repo.

90
00:06:01,258 --> 00:06:05,187
For example: curl create-docs and verify-codex,

91
00:06:05,299 --> 00:06:09,823
pipe to claude — with the dangerously-skip-permissions flag.

92
00:06:11,242 --> 00:06:14,224
The markdown URLs will be shortened in the near future.

93
00:06:15,009 --> 00:06:19,824
That one command generates full Progressive Disclosure docs for any repo and

94
00:06:19,903 --> 00:06:23,028
runs cross-model verification — end to end,

95
00:06:23,096 --> 00:06:26,390
about fifty minutes, zero human intervention.

96
00:06:27,057 --> 00:06:31,994
We're not providing skills or slash commands — but they could easily

97
00:06:32,047 --> 00:06:35,985
be hooked up to the master prompt files depending on your implementation

98
00:06:36,052 --> 00:06:37,509
preferences.

99
00:06:38,585 --> 00:06:39,983
Visible prompts are accountable.

100
00:06:40,062 --> 00:06:43,342
Hidden skills may or may not be followed.

101
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:47,912
Engineers should read the prompts, not trust hidden instructions.

102
00:06:48,114 --> 00:06:49,993
Here's how to start.

103
00:06:51,049 --> 00:06:51,913
Pick a repo.

104
00:06:53,805 --> 00:06:57,437
Use the create-docs prompt chained with a verify prompt,

105
00:06:57,490 --> 00:06:59,672
as shown in the ai-devkit readme.

106
00:07:01,393 --> 00:07:05,273
Let it run — and now you have Progressive Disclosure docs enabling

107
00:07:05,373 --> 00:07:08,315
any agent to work effectively in that repo.

108
00:07:10,036 --> 00:07:14,307
Add specs and test-driven implementation using the relevant prompts.

109
00:07:16,097 --> 00:07:21,026
Build your AI Dev Environment to run multi-repo systems end to end.

110
00:07:22,925 --> 00:07:33,582
The repo, the standard, and all the prompts are open at github.com/AgoraIO-Community/ai-devkit.

111
00:07:35,328 --> 00:07:36,063
Goodbye for now.

112
00:07:37,315 --> 00:07:38,784
Questions gratefully received.

113
00:07:39,327 --> 00:07:42,061
And look out for upcoming deeper topic dives.

